{
  "texts": [
    "These enhancements allow models to better handle the complexities of fossil morphology while preserving accuracy.",
    "From a paleontological perspective, segmentation techniques have enabled more precise reconstruction of fossil structures at a higher rate, and so larger sample sizes, both of which are crucial for understanding evolutionary relationships, palaeoecology, and functional morphology.",
    "For example, segmenting vertebrate microfossils from high-resolution CT data has facilitated the quantitative analysis of bone histology, aiding studies on growth patterns and pathological conditions in extinct species.",
    "Similarly, automated workflows for isolating fossils from surrounding matrices have provided more efficient ways to analyze large datasets, such as microfossil assemblages used in biostratigraphy and paleoenvironmental reconstructions.",
    "A notable advancement in fossil segmentation has been the integration of 3D convolutional networks, which allow for the processing of volumetric data obtained from CT scans and similar 3D imaging modalities."
  ]
}